<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910522-0113</DOCNO><DOCID>910522-0113.</DOCID><HL>   Dayton Hudson Net   Fell in May Quarter;   Special Costs Cited</HL><DATE>05/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   DH</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>MINNESOTA (MN)</RE><LP>   MINNEAPOLIS -- Dayton Hudson Corp. said its fiscalfirst-quarter earnings dropped by nearly half from lastyear's first quarter, largely because of the costs of itsMarshall Field acquisition and a soft retail market.   Despite the drop in earnings, the retailer's stock rose $2to $74.125 in composite trading on the New York StockExchange because the results were slightly better than someanalysts had projected. The company said earnings in thequarter, ended May 4, dropped to $34 million, or 39 cents ashare, from $60 million, or 76 cents a share, in theyear-earlier period. The 1990 results included a one-timegain of $2 million, or four cents a share, from an accountingchange.</LP><TEXT>   Per-share earnings in this year's quarter reflected a15-cent reduction because of additional interest expenseinvolving Marshall Field and an additional 10-cent decreasebecause of increased funding of Dayton Hudson's employeestock ownership plan.   Total revenue increased 11% to $3.35 billion from $3billion in last year's first quarter. Comparable-storerevenue, which includes stores open for a year or more,increased only 1%, Dayton Hudson said.   The company said it expects a &quot;difficult&quot; second quarteras well, but declined to provide more detailed information.The company said its sales have been particularly hard-hit inCalifornia, where it does a third of its business.   Dayton Hudson said total revenue at its Target storesincreased 5%, but comparable-store revenues increased only2%. Target's operating profit was down because of increaseddiscounting and additional expenses for a new distributionfacility in Tifton, Ga., and new customer service programs,the company said. The company doesn't disclose specificearnings results for Target or its other operating divisionson a quarterly basis.   Total revenue increased 2% at its Mervyn's stores, whichposted &quot;slightly improved&quot; operating profit because ofadditional cost controls, the company said. Total revenue ofits overall department store division increased 61%, butoperating profit declined because of increased expenses.</TEXT></DOC>